	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Sector adjustment support to Caribbean rum sector yields sustainable benefits</h1>

			
			<h4>
												25 December 2010
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>Press reports suggest that the emphasis placed on shifting to quality-differentiated production in the Caribbean rum sector, promoted through the EU-financed Integrated Development Programme for the Caribbean Rum Sector, has begun to bear fruit. Reports in October highlighted the success being enjoyed by Mount Gay Distilleries in promoting its Mount Gay Rum Extra Old. According to Mount Gay Distilleries’ Managing Director, Raphael Grisoni, ‘internationally, Mount Gay is doing well and growing in key markets’. It was only in 2005 that Barbados rum export sales first exceeded $50 million. By 2008, rum export sales had grown to $67 million, before falling back to $57 million with the onset of the global economic downturn. However rum exports showed a strong recovery in the first five months of 2010, with sales expected to exceed $60 million on an annualised basis.</p><p>According to press reports, this consolidation of the market position of quality-differentiated Caribbean rums has been achieved by a combination of efforts of individual company managers and the financial support for marketing adjustments financed under the West Indies Rum and Spirits Producers’ Association (WIRSPA)-administered and EU-financed Caribbean Rum Marque campaign.</p><p>Similar achievements in enhancing its market position have been reported in the case of Guyana’s premium rum producer, Demerara Distillers. It was reported that recently an agreement had been reached between Demerara Distillers Ltd (DDL) and Sandals Resort International ‘under which El Dorado will be the exclusive pouring rum at all Sandals Resorts’. In addition, the Guyanese premium brand El Dorado will ‘occupy prime positions in all Sandals Gift Shops at its resorts located in Jamaica, the Bahamas, Antigua, Saint Lucia, and the Turks and Caicos Islands.’</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>
Barbados Advocate, ‘Mount Gay seeing positive response to new packaging’, 25 October 2010<br />

<a href="http://www.barbadosadvocate.com/newsitem.asp?more=business&amp;NewsID=13607" target="_self">http://www.barbadosadvocate.com/newsitem.asp?more=business&amp;NewsID=13607</a>&nbsp;<br />
Barbados Advocate, ‘Rum pushes ahead’, 16 November 2010<br />

<a href="http://www.barbadosadvocate.com/newsitem.asp?more=business&amp;NewsID=14042" target="_self">http://www.barbadosadvocate.com/newsitem.asp?more=business&amp;NewsID=14042</a><br />
Stabroek News, ‘Chamber President salutes DDL’s Sandals achievement’, 1 October 2010<br />
<a href="http://www.stabroeknews.com/2010/business/10/01/chamber-president-salutes-ddl%E2%80%99s-sandals-achievement/" target="_self">http://www.stabroeknews.com/2010/business/10/01/chamber-president-salute...</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>The €70 million in pump-priming support extended to production and marketing adjustments under the Integrated Development Programme for the Caribbean Rum Sector has proved critical in promoting and supporting the development of forward-looking marketing and production adjustment strategies across a range of participating Caribbean rum sector companies. The achievement of export sales growth of around 34% in Barbados over a three-year period, and the resumption of export sales growth so rapidly after the onset of the global economic downturn, implies that a sustainable structural transformation in the market position of quality-differentiated Caribbean rum producers is under way.</p><p>It is in Barbados that the first production and trade adjustment initiatives supported under the programme took place. This was a by-product of the physical location of the WIRSPA secretariat on the island, which facilitated the establishment of direct support measures in the early days of this innovative regional programme. However, the repositioning of the Guyanese El Dorado brand, as shown by the recent agreement with Sandal Resorts, is also indicative of the market repositioning that can be achieved within the framework of a coordinated regional strategy for the repositioning of long-established domestic production in the light of evolving market trends and the post-preference trade realities.</p>
		</div>
		
